{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_85","type":"agent_message","text":"I added [reachability-metadata.json](/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge2/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/forge_worktrees/4803-8d74babf/metadata/org.apache.camel/camel-health/4.20.0/reachability-metadata.json:1) for `org.apache.camel:camel-health:4.20.0`. It registers the health-check implementation constructors under `org.apache.camel.support.ObjectHelper` and adds `META-INF/services/org/apache/camel/health-check/*` resources for the direct resolver path. That fixes the native failure behind `registryRegistersDirectChecksRepositoriesAndAppliesLookupAndExclusionRules()`.\n\nI verified every run with the exact required GraalVM; `native-image --version` matched `25.0.3 2026-04-21 / Oracle GraalVM 25.1.0-dev+9.1`. The full reproduction still does **not** pass:\n`./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.apache.camel:camel-health:4.20.0`\n\nThe remaining failure is `defaultLoaderDiscoversClasspathHealthChecksFromCamelServiceDescriptors()`. I built a separate native probe with the same GraalVM and metadata and confirmed the root cause: in native image, `ClassLoader.getResources(\"META-INF/services/org/apache/camel/health-check/\")` returns `resource:/...`, and Camel’s `DefaultPackageScanResourceResolver` cannot walk that protocol as a jar or directory, so `findResources(\".../*-check\")` returns `0` even though the specific descriptor file is present and readable. That means the last failure is a Camel package-scan limitation under native image, not a remaining missing metadata entry.\n\nI left `tests/src/org.apache.camel/camel-health/4.20.0/user-code-filter.json` untouched; it was already locally modified before I started."}}
